 {"id":"bd-x7jd","title":"POSIX/hosts(5) conformance table for /etc/hosts parser","description":"frankenlibc-core::resolv has unit tests for parse_hosts_line/lookup_hosts but no spec-annotated conformance table. Add Pattern-4 spec-derived table with cases citing hosts(5) + RFC 952 + RFC 1123 (hostname validation). Coverage: whitespace (spaces/tabs/mixed), case insensitivity, IPv4/IPv6 mix, multi-alias lines, comments (start/mid-line), blank lines, CRLF, malformed addresses, RFC 952/1123 hostname char set. Scope: crates/frankenlibc-core/src/resolv/mod.rs #[cfg(test)] module. One commit per section group.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-20T19:25:33.676462834Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-20T19:29:43.474768096Z","closed_at":"2026-04-20T19:29:43.472712968Z","close_reason":"Added 3 POSIX/resolver(5)/hosts(5) spec-derived conformance tables across 2 commits: ad881c2 (hosts parse 16 cases + lookup 7 cases), 0b464ba (resolv.conf 12 cases). Total 35 cases with spec_ref citations for hosts(5), RFC 952, RFC 1123, RFC 1035, resolver(5), and <resolv.h> MAXNS cap.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"bd-x8z63","title":"PORT: res_gethostbyname/2/by_addr + res_send_set{q,r}hook + ns_name_ntol + ns_name_rollback","description":"Add five libresolv res_*/ns_* aliases + name helpers. (1) res_gethostbyname(name) -> wrapper around gethostbyname. (2) res_gethostbyname2(name, af) -> wrapper around gethostbyname2. (3) res_gethostbyaddr(addr, len, type) -> wrapper around gethostbyaddr. These three are the deprecated res_-prefixed forms that early BIND used; modern callers use the un-prefixed forms but the symbols are still exported by libresolv.so.2. (4) res_send_setqhook(qhook) and (5) res_send_setrhook(rhook) install pre-query / post-response hook callbacks; modern glibc accepts but largely ignores them — provide a thread-local store with a getter for tests. (6) ns_name_ntol(src, dst, dstsiz) -> int converts a wire-format domain name (length-prefixed labels terminated by a 0 length byte) to lowercase, copying into dst. Returns 0 on success, -1 on truncation. (7) ns_name_rollback(ptr, dnptrs, lastdnptr) walks dnptrs[] backwards and zeroes out any entry whose value is at or past `ptr`, used to undo partial name compression entries on error paths.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"feature","created_at":"2026-04-26T15:53:23.100036968Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T15:58:17.301690530Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T15:58:17.299483851Z","close_reason":"shipped: 7 libresolv entries (res_gethostby* x3 + res_send_set{q,r}hook + ns_name_ntol + ns_name_rollback) + 11 abi tests, all green","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"bd-x9vt","title":"resolv: characterize NULL gaicb policy for gai_error without crashing tests","description":"Host gai_error(NULL) appears unsafe or crash-prone, while FrankenLibC currently returns a safe ENOSYS fallback. Determine the documented policy for this NULL-handle edge without destabilizing the test harness, then codify the expected behavior.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-21T06:27:55.762351969Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-21T17:42:44.680688756Z","closed_at":"2026-04-21T17:42:44.678520136Z","close_reason":"Characterized host gai_error(NULL) via subprocess probe and codified FrankenLibC safe NULL-handle policy.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
-{"id":"bd-xapiq","title":"PORT: 8 libcrypt aliases + DES no-op stubs + crypt_preferred_method + crypt_checksalt","description":"Add 8 libcrypt aliases / fail-safe stubs to close part of the libcrypt parity gap. Our existing crypt() already supports MD5/SHA-256/SHA-512; these add the historical names + DES no-ops + utility queries that programs commonly link against without actually invoking crypto. (1) fcrypt(key, salt) — alias of crypt. (2) xcrypt(key, salt) — same. (3) encrypt(block, edflag) — no-op (DES single-block; DES is obsolete and our crypt rejects it anyway). (4) encrypt_r(block, edflag, *data) — no-op. (5) setkey(key) — no-op. (6) setkey_r(key, *data) — no-op. (7) crypt_preferred_method() -> *const c_char — return the static string \"$6$\" (SHA-512 = our strongest supported method). (8) crypt_checksalt(setting) -> int — parse the salt prefix; return CRYPT_SALT_OK (= 0) for $1$/$5$/$6$ and CRYPT_SALT_INVALID (= 1) otherwise per libxcrypt convention.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"feature","created_at":"2026-04-26T17:53:20.521744556Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T17:53:20.521744556Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
+{"id":"bd-xapiq","title":"PORT: 8 libcrypt aliases + DES no-op stubs + crypt_preferred_method + crypt_checksalt","description":"Add 8 libcrypt aliases / fail-safe stubs to close part of the libcrypt parity gap. Our existing crypt() already supports MD5/SHA-256/SHA-512; these add the historical names + DES no-ops + utility queries that programs commonly link against without actually invoking crypto. (1) fcrypt(key, salt) — alias of crypt. (2) xcrypt(key, salt) — same. (3) encrypt(block, edflag) — no-op (DES single-block; DES is obsolete and our crypt rejects it anyway). (4) encrypt_r(block, edflag, *data) — no-op. (5) setkey(key) — no-op. (6) setkey_r(key, *data) — no-op. (7) crypt_preferred_method() -> *const c_char — return the static string \"$6$\" (SHA-512 = our strongest supported method). (8) crypt_checksalt(setting) -> int — parse the salt prefix; return CRYPT_SALT_OK (= 0) for $1$/$5$/$6$ and CRYPT_SALT_INVALID (= 1) otherwise per libxcrypt convention.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"feature","created_at":"2026-04-26T17:53:20.521744556Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T17:57:20.563761936Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T17:57:20.561680248Z","close_reason":"shipped: 8 libcrypt entries (fcrypt + xcrypt aliases of real crypt; encrypt/encrypt_r/setkey/setkey_r DES no-ops; crypt_preferred_method static '$'; crypt_checksalt classifier) + 5 abi tests","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"bd-xat1","title":"CONFORMANCE: libc sys/xattr.h diff matrix","description":"Differential harness shipped (see commit). 7 functions: setxattr/getxattr/listxattr/removexattr (path-based round-trip via cross fl-set + lc-get; size-query then name-set parsing for listxattr; missing-attr ENOATTR edge), fsetxattr/fgetxattr (fd-based round-trip). Probes filesystem ENOTSUP support and skips cleanly if xattrs unavailable. 5 tests, 0 divergences against glibc.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"cod-frankenlibc","created_at":"2026-04-24T13:30:00Z","created_by":"cod-frankenlibc","updated_at":"2026-04-24T13:30:00Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T13:30:00Z","close_reason":"Harness shipped; 0 divergences.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["conformance","differential","xattr"]}
 {"id":"bd-xejg","title":"socket: execute socket_ops.json fixture family through harness matrix","description":"Concrete gap: crates/frankenlibc-harness/tests/socket_ops_conformance_test.rs only validates socket fixture metadata even though the shared conformance executor covers socket/bind/listen/shutdown cases. Add isolated harness subprocess execution for tests/conformance/fixtures/socket_ops.json, assert expected_output and host parity in strict/hardened modes, and fix any socket parity regressions exposed by the harness path.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-21T04:12:06.315894551Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-23T22:11:18.746159330Z","closed_at":"2026-04-23T22:11:18.743945851Z","close_reason":"Verified: crates/frankenlibc-harness/tests/socket_ops_conformance_test.rs lines 263-423 execute every socket_ops fixture case through both execute_fixture_case (in-process) and the harness conformance-matrix-case subprocess; all 14 tests pass with expected_output equality and host_parity assertions in strict+hardened modes (commit 1c5a9d0f). Run: rch exec -- env CARGO_TARGET_DIR=/tmp/rch_target_harness cargo test -p frankenlibc-harness --test socket_ops_conformance_test -> 14/0 passed in 0.13s.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"bd-xgmqc","title":"CONFORMANCE: libc signal.h sigset helpers diff matrix","description":"Differential harness shipped in commit eed4de57. 6 functions (sigemptyset/sigfillset/sigaddset/sigdelset/sigismember/strsignal). Caught + tightened comparator on the documented userspace-vs-kernel sigset_t initialization quality-of-implementation difference (glibc leaves bytes 8..128 uninitialized; FrankenLibC zeros them; both POSIX-conformant). Zero real divergences after tightening.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"cod-frankenlibc","created_at":"2026-04-24T05:30:00Z","created_by":"cod-frankenlibc","updated_at":"2026-04-24T05:30:00Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T05:30:00Z","close_reason":"Harness shipped in commit eed4de57; 0 real divergences after kernel-sigset comparator tightening.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["conformance","differential","signal"]}
